 History                                                            50 1451     
 -------                                                            50 1451     
 This evaluation was produced at Bettis Atomic Power Laboratory in  50 1451     
 October 2016 using the LEAPR module of NJOY2012 [1].  The phonon   50 1451     
 frequency spectra for H and O in solid H2O (ice Ih) were           50 1451     
 calculated using the MedeA materials simulation software [2] and   50 1451     
 and optimized as described in Ref. 3.  This evaluation has been    50 1451     
 validated against measured total cross sections [3,4] and flux     50 1451     
 decay time eigenvalues for a pulsed-neutron die-away diffusion     50 1451     
 experiment [3,5].                                                  50 1451     
                                                                    50 1451     
 Theory                                                             50 1451     
 ------                                                             50 1451     
 The phase of solid H2O encountered under common temperature and    50 1451     
 pressure conditions is ice Ih, a hexagonal structure with locally  50 1451     
 ordered but globally disordered molecular orientations.  The VASP  50 1451     
 ab initio density functional theory code and PHONON lattice        50 1451     
 dynamics code were used to calculate the phonon spectra for H and  50 1451     
 O in ice Ih with constraints based on high-accuracy measured       50 1451     
 lattice constants [3,6].  The same phonon spectra are used at all  50 1451     
 temperatures because thermal expansion is negligible.  The         50 1451     
 calculated spectra were then optimized to be consistent with       50 1451     
 experimentally measured inelastic neutron scattering spectra [7]   50 1451     
 and total cross sections [4] for physical samples with globally    50 1451     
 disordered H positions.                                            50 1451     
                                                                    50 1451     
